author: BrzVlad
body:
This issue tracks required work and progress for the porting of the mono interpreter to CoreCLR. The end goal of this issue is to be able to run entire test suites in full interpreter mode (without any JIT/AOT) on desktop platforms (ex. arm64 linux). This issue will be updated on the fly as the implementation progresses.

### M1 - basic compilation and interpreting support of a simple method
- [x] interp wire-in https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/112202 https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/112369
- [x] interp executor in libcoreclr https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/112369
- [x] interpreter runtime test https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/112369
### M2 - stress tests involving object manipulation
- [x] constant loads and unchecked binops https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/113292
- [x] ldlocal/ldarg https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/113292
- [x] static direct calls https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/113292
- [x] full var offset allocator https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/113292
- [x] basic block formation and implementation of branch opcodes https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/113292
- [x] newobj creation https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/114049
- [x] field access opcodes https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/114049
- [x] indirect load/store opcodes https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/114049
- [x] precise GC scanning https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/114469
- [x] GC safepoints https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/115567
- [x] conversion opcodes https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/113292
- [x] valuetypes (locals, fields, ctor) https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/114049
- [x] basic generics working https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/116357 and https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/issues/116395
- [x] static fields https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/114049
### M3 - EH and interpreter calls
- [x] basic non exceptional path for try/finally/leave #116046
- [x] exception throw support and resume to correct handler clause  #116046
- [x] implement invocation of finally/filter clauses from EH  #116046
- [x] null checks and ovf opcodes - #116046
- [x] interp virtual call support https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/114529
- [x] interp interface call support https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/114529
- [x] direct calls to non-interp code #115375
### M4 - mixing with compiled code
- [x] figure out separation between interp/jit/R2R code for testing purposes #116769
- [x] calli and ldftn with interpreter target method #116449 
- [x] calli and ldftn with jitted target method #116449 
- [x] delegate creation and invocation with interpreter target method #116449
- [x] other delegate scenarios, passing it between interp/jit with either interpreted or jitted target method #116449
### M5 - pinvoke support, full interpreter support for Hello World
- [x] implement pinvoke support https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/115393
- [x] implement reverse pinvoke support https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/119133
- [x] bugfixes and feature support for `Console.WriteLine("Hello World")` in full interpreter mode
### M6 - IL opcodes for CoreCLR startup ordered by number of occurrences:
- [x] array support https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/115553
  - [x] ldlen
  - [x] newarr
  - [x] stelem
  - [x] ldelem
- [x] array ref support https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/116384
  - [x] ldelema
  - [x] ldelem.ref
  - [x] stelem.ref
  - [x] get
  - [x] set
- [x] ldtoken https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/115723
- [x] isinst #116046
- [x] castclass
- [x] box, unbox https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/115549
- [x] sizeof https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/115745
- [x] ldobj, stobj https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/115900
- [x] cpobj https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/119025
- [x] localloc https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/114860
- [x] floating point conversion opcodes #116356
- [x] mkrefany, refanyval, refanytype https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/118753
- [x] cpblk https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/118404
- [x] initblk https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/119025
- [ ] ckfinite
- [x] constrained calls #116702
- [ ] volatile prefix and memory barriers
- [x] tailcall prefix
- [x] interpreter->interpreter tailcalls
- [ ] interpreter->native tailcalls
- [ ] native->interpreter tailcalls
- [ ] readonly prefix
- [x] bugfixes and feature support for test suites
  - [x] ldc.r8 with double.MinValue return NaN https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/116115

---

#### Nice to have refactorings/improvements that are out of scope of this project:
- Remove the usage of StackType, we could rely exclusively on the InterpType instead
- Optimize reimportation. Use a graph clique approach similar to RyuJIT, rather than naive retries.

Currently, CoreCLR generates some executable code at runtime besides the JITted code. This work stream will provide alternative approaches for platforms that don't allow runtime executable code generation.

- [x] Alternative to the way fixup and stub precodes and call counting stubs are generated. #115746
- [x] Alternative GC write barrier #114982
### M4

### M5
- [ ] Alternative to ShuffleThunks + Non-IL based Unboxing stubs
- [ ] Modify debugger code to work properly with all the changes made to prevent executable code generation at runtime.

### M5

title: CoreCLR Interpreter - diagnostics

author: janvorli
body:
CoreCLR runtime doesn’t currently support platforms that don’t allow runtime executable code generation, like iOS, macCatalyst or WASM. There are runtime helpers and stubs that are generated by the runtime. And even with ReadyToRun (R2R) assemblies, JIT is still needed for some cases where crossgen cannot precompile methods for various reasons.

To allow usage of CoreCLR runtime on such platforms, it was decided to implement an interpreter for CoreCLR. During an experiment last autumn, the Mono interpreter was analyzed in detail, and it was decided that it can be used as a basis for a new CoreCLR interpreter implementation. 

Besides interpreter implementation, it is also necessary to make CoreCLR capable of working without any runtime executable code generation. So, part of the work focuses on replacing or reimplementing the helpers so that no executable code is generated at runtime.

Natural part of the work is also ensuring that diagnostic tools can work with the interpreter. These tools include the SOS plugin and debugger related code in the CoreCLR responsible for setting breakpoints, single stepping, examining locals and arguments in the frames of interpreted functions and viewing stack trace with interpreted methods on the stack. More complex scenarios like EnC are out of scope of the work in .NET 10 timeframe.

The planned work is divided into five workstreams:
* CoreCLR runtime changes (excluding diagnostics)
* Mono interpreter porting
* Ensuring CoreCLR doesn’t generate any executable code at runtime
* Diagnostics
* iOS with CoreCLR
* WASM with CoreCLR

The work is split into six milestones (M1 to M6). The actual work is tracked by sub-issues per each workstream:

* Interpreter itself - #112158
* CoreCLR support for the interpreter - #112742
* Preventing executable code generation at runtime - #112743
* Diagnostics support for the interpreter - #112744
* Enabling CoreCLR on WASM - https://github.com/orgs/dotnet/projects/520
* Ensuring the coreclr startup path can be fully interpreted - #117556

nodes.author: CeSun
nodes.body: Does this mean that programs published by NativeAOT can dynamically load dll(il)?

nodes.author: janvorli
nodes.body: @CeSun we are currently adding interpreter for CoreCLR, not for NativeAOT. NativeAOT is missing a lot of functionality e.g. around IL metadata that the interpreter needs.

nodes.author: filipnavara
nodes.body:
> NativeAOT is missing a lot of functionality e.g. around IL metadata that the interpreter needs.

Additionally, NativeAOT operates strictly on trimmed code where the "whole world view" is based on static analysis at compile time. Any dynamic code wouldn't be able to access API surface outside of the trimmed code.

nodes.author: CeSun
nodes.body:
I don't understand the purpose of adding an interpreter to coreclr. On platforms that prohibit JIT (such as iOS), if all .NET programs are interpreted and executed, will the running efficiency be acceptable?

I personally think that the acceptable solution is: the main program is released by NativeAOT to ensure performance; a small part of the code that needs hot update or dynamic loading requirements is executed by the interpreter.

nodes.author: filipnavara
nodes.body:
> I don't understand the purpose of adding an interpreter to coreclr.

Same purpose as MonoVM uses it today - debugging mobile and WASM applications.

nodes.author: janvorli
nodes.body:
> I don't understand the purpose of adding an interpreter to coreclr. On platforms that prohibit JIT (such as iOS), if all .NET programs are interpreted and executed, will the running efficiency be acceptable?

Running everything interpreted is not the end goal. We will have a combination of precompiled managed code with only some of the code being interpreted. The precompiled code will be the R2R and not NativeAOT though. We plan to add support for R2R on iOS in the .NET 11 timeframe.

nodes.author: CeSun
nodes.body:
> We plan to add support for R2R on iOS in the .NET 11 timeframe.

Great! Can R2R be easily embedded into other host programs? 

Because game development requires a .NET runtime that supports multiple platforms (windows, ios, android, even switch and PS) and supports dynamic loading of IL (hot update is a very important function for game applications).

nodes.author: janvorli
nodes.body:
> Can R2R be easily embedded into other host programs?

We currently have a single file host that can already do that for CoreCLR on other platforms if you opt for that when publishing your app. For iOS, this kind of deployment will be used too, although we still need to design some changes to the R2R so that it can be loaded on iOS and other platforms that don't allow executable code generation at runtime.

author: davidwrighton
body:
Basic shared generics support will be in once PR #116357 is merged, but there remain a number of additional issues

- [x] Support for box with a generic type which varies by type parameter
- [x] Support for unbox.any with a generic type which varies by type parameter
- [x] Support for isinst with a generic type which varies by type parameter
- [x] Support for castclass with a generic type which varies by type parameter
- [x] Support for static fields on a type which varies by type parameter
- [x] Support for callvirt fallback to ldvirtftn behavior, will probably require adding support for the ldvirtftn opcode + calli opcode
- [x] Support for constrained calls to classes
- [x] Support for constrained calls to static virtual methods defined on classes. will probably require adding support for the calli opcode
- [ ] Support for IL stub implementations of unboxing/unboxing and instantiating helpers
- [x] Support for constrained dispatch to structs from generic code, particularly with shared generics involved. Will involve respecting the `CORINFO_THIS_TRANSFORM` returned from `getCallInfo`
- [ ] Handling of catch of a generic where which generic is dependent on the context argument to the method

title: Test failure: JIT/interpreter/InterpreterTester/InterpreterTester.cmd

author: kg
body: ArenaAllocator (alloc.h/alloc.cpp in src/coreclr/jit) is something we want to use in the interpreter, so it needs to be moved out of the JIT into a new `jitshared` folder. This will require a bit of tricky work to extract its dependencies on JIT-specific stuff.

title: Migrate ArenaAllocator out of JIT into JITshared

author: kg
body:
A discussion in the P/Invoke PR indicates that there is more work to be done in the future even after it's landed, around marshaling wrappers, the prestub, and other places. See https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/115393#discussion_r2095973029 and https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/115393#discussion_r2096046465.

Relevant bits quoted below.

> I expect that we will need to do something about the hidden IL stub arguments and PInvoke IL stub sharing to make the marshalling stubs work. The easiest path may be to disable PInvoke IL stub sharing in interpreter mode (or get rid of it completely - it may not be as important as it used to be).

> The interpreter related code in prestub.cpp (and other places) is not prepared to handle PInvokes.
> We should agree on how we are going to deal with sharing of marshalling stubs first; and then do the required changes.

title: CoreCLR interpreter - unresolved questions/work around P/Invoke

author: kg
body:
As pointed out by @jkotas in the https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/117727#discussion_r2223709887 thread on PR #117727, if we bounce between running jitted/compiled code for intrinsics and interpreting them, this will produce inconsistent IsSupported/IsHardwareAccelerated return values and as a result inconsistent application behavior or crashes.

The most likely shipping configuration will be R2R + interpreter, so we need to make sure that in this configuration we R2R-compile every intrinsic that might possibly get used, so the interpreter can invoke the R2R'd code for all intrinsics where possible.

author: kg
body:
When using mixed mode debugging with the interpreter, you'll get a lot of spurious assertions that look like this:

```
Debug Assertion Failed!

Program: ...s\tests\coreclr\windows.x64.Debug\Tests\Core_Root\coreclr.dll
File: Z:\runtime\src\coreclr\debug\ee\debugger.h
Line: 1404

Expression: !"addressToOffset called with invalid address"
```

If you ignore them execution will continue and everything works. Probably not important but wanted to log it anyway.

title: Mixed mode debugging errors with the interpreter

author: kg
body:
This is a list (not all inclusive and in no particular order) of limitations in the interpreter and/or runtime that we don't *currently* plan to address but may make plans to address in the future.

- [ ] Tiered compilation causes crashes in the interpreter if it recompiles an interpreted method. *We currently disable tiered compilation if the interpreter is enabled at all.*
- [ ] Many invocations go through stubs that don't need to, i.e. interpreter-to-interpreter invocations of pinvokes or delegates. *This will need to be addressed eventually for WASM and iOS but is not currently causing problems.*
- [ ] Mixed-mode debugging does not work reliably and will trigger assertions or fail to properly walk the stack.
- [ ] We do not put debug fill patterns (0xCDCDCDCD) in place of local variables that have their address exposed like the JIT does. This breaks JIT\Directed\debugging\poisoning\poison.
- [ ] Varargs, managed C++, exception handling interop, and other Windows specific runtime features

title: [interp] Limitations we're not planning to address right now

author: kotlarmilos
body:
## Description

This issue tracks the progress of enabling the CoreCLR interpreter on Apple mobile.


## Tasks
 - [ ] Update the build system to statically link the interpreter into `libcoreclr.dylib` for Debug builds and into the app bundle for Release builds. In that case, `LoadAndInitializeJIT` won’t be used on devices
 - [ ] Rename Mono/iossimulator-specific functions
 - [ ] Include ICU library in the app bundle
 - [ ] Test x64 simulator architectures
 - [ ] Add support for tvOS/tvOS simulator
 - [ ] Fix `async Task<int> Main`

nodes.author: jkotas
nodes.body:
> the static library path (InitializeStaticJIT) or the dynamic library path (LoadAndInitializeJIT) through hard-coded macros

Is this about the JIT (libclrjit.dylib) or about the whole runtime (libcoreclr.dylib)? 

I agree that we want to option to have runtime in a dynamic library (libcoreclr.dylib) that just gets copied over for F5 scenarios and for our own internal testing.

I do not see the value of providing app-configurable options for having dynamically linked JIT vs. statically linked JIT. What would be the scenario for that?

nodes.author: kotlarmilos
nodes.body:
Sorry, I wasn’t explicit about the components. I was thinking about the compiler (both JIT and interpreter) and runtime.

The main considerations are extensibility and performance. On simulators and MacCatalyst, JIT is allowed. With dynamic linking, we could statically link the JIT while loading the interpreter dynamically. This would require shipping both dynamic and static libraries: the runtime and interpreter for devices; the runtime, interpreter, and JIT for simulators. The linking mode would then be selected at app build time. To support this, the current approach in `codeman.cpp` for loading the compiler would need to change. Instead of hard-coded macros for Apple mobile, we would use an app-build property. WASM would remain restricted to static linking only.

On the performance side, I’m also wondering whether dynamically linking the interpreter (and possibly other components) could reduce build times in Debug configurations.

nodes.author: jkotas
nodes.body:
> I’m also wondering whether dynamically linking the interpreter (and possibly other components) could reduce build times in Debug configurations.

Right, we want to have dynamic libraries (libcoreclr.dylib, etc.) for debug app configuration, and static linking of everything for release app configuration. 

I do not think we need to have different linking of the JIT between these two configurations. The JIT can be statically linked in both cases (statically linked into libcoreclr.dylib for F5, and into the app itself for release). I agree that dynamic linking of the JIT would work for F5 too, but I do not see why it is required. It would make the file layout more similar to non-device OSes Windows/Linux/macOS and we can do it for that as nice-to-have.

nodes.author: kotlarmilos
nodes.body: Ok, thanks. It makes sense to statically link the compiler into libcoreclr.dylib for Debug builds and into the app bundle for Release builds. In that case, `LoadAndInitializeJIT` won’t be used on devices. I’ll update the description and use this as the tracking issue.

title: [clr-interp] Enable building CoreCLR for Apple mobile

author: kg
body:
As currently written, InterpreterStub looks like it will crash if it's called on a thread that does not have a managed thread set up yet. This results in TheUMEntryPrestubWorker needing to manually set up the thread before tail calling the InterpreterStub for interpreted reverse p/invoke.

See https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/119133/files#r2308314591
